## 9. `docs/AI_STATUS.md` Discipline

Read `docs/AI_STATUS.md` at the start of every new session before
taking any action. If it does not exist, create it before proceeding.

After every completed task, update it with:

```markdown
## Current Phase
Phase X — [Phase Name]

## CURRENT_ARCHITECTURE_SNAPSHOT
[High-level summary of what is actually built vs. planned]

## SCHEMA_DRIFT_LOG
- [Date] [Task X.X] — Contract says `<entity>.<column>` is `<type>`;
  generated types say `<other-type>`. Resolved by: [used types,
  contract update pending | needs human decision | other].
  Status: [open | resolved in <task>].

## KNOWN_ISSUES
- [Date] [Task X.X] — [Issue description] — [open | resolved].

## Completed Tasks
- [Task ID]: [One-sentence description of what was built]
```

`SCHEMA_DRIFT_LOG` is separate from `KNOWN_ISSUES` because drift is
load-bearing. A UX bug surfaces at runtime; drift produces silent
wrong behaviour. It must be visible and resolvable on its own track.

**Drift log discipline:**

1. Every disagreement encountered between the contract, the live
   schema, the generated types, or user instruction goes into
   `SCHEMA_DRIFT_LOG` immediately on detection.
2. At Task X.99 (phase close), every `SCHEMA_DRIFT_LOG` entry MUST
   either be marked resolved (with the task that resolved it) or
   explicitly deferred with a one-line reason.
3. Any drift entry deferred for more than two consecutive phases is
   surfaced as a blocker at the start of the next phase. Long-lived
   unresolved drift produces compounding inconsistency.

Keep `AI_STATUS.md` accurate. This file is the only persistent memory
between sessions. It is also the audit trail: when something breaks
three weeks from now, the drift log is what tells you whether the
breakage was predicted and ignored, or genuinely new.

