## 13. Tool-Call Efficiency — Minimize Permission Prompts

Every permission-gated tool call interrupts the user. Reduce the count by batching where it is safe to do so.

**Chain related shell commands.** When several read or inspection commands run in sequence and none depends on the structured output of another, combine them into a single Bash call with `&&` (or `;` when failure tolerance is acceptable). One approval, one context switch.

- Yes: `git status --short && git log --oneline -5 && ls docs/`
- No: three separate Bash calls for the same three pieces of information.

**Use parallel tool calls for independent work.** When two or more tool calls do not depend on each other (reading three unrelated files, running typecheck alongside lint, running two unrelated greps), issue them in a single response so they execute concurrently. This eliminates wall-clock pauses even when each call still prompts individually.

**Never chain destructive or hard-to-reverse actions.** A `git push`, a `supabase db push` or any migration apply, a `git reset --hard`, a `git restore`, a file or directory deletion (`rm`, `rm -rf`), a package install or upgrade, and any force flag must each be its own tool call so the user can approve or decline it individually. Routine local writes — `git add`, `git commit`, file edits via Edit/Write — may be chained with each other and with reads (e.g. `git add X && git commit -m '...' && git status --short`).

**Announce long tool sequences up front.** When more than three permission-gated calls are about to fire in a row, lead with a one-line plan ("running typecheck, lint, and build, then committing") so the user can batch the mental approval rather than context-switching on every prompt.

### Prefer native tools to shell pipelines for file work

**TL;DR — before constructing any shell pipeline against the filesystem, stop. If the work is reading, writing, editing, searching, or listing files, the answer is a native tool, not the shell. Shell is exclusively for git, builds, and process control. Re-reach for the shell only after you've ruled out the native tool.**

For any operation that touches the filesystem — reading, writing, editing, searching, listing — use the native Claude Code tools, not a shell pipeline. Native tools produce **zero** permission prompts and handle paths with shell-special characters (`(app)`, `[tenant]`, backticks, `$`) without escaping. The shell parser will literally fail on `ls /path/(app)/foo` and `grep ... /path/(app)/...` — those characters open a subshell. There is no escape that fixes it cleanly; quoting works but the native tools are simpler.

| You want to | Use | Not |
|---|---|---|
| Read a file or a range of lines | `Read` with `offset`/`limit` | `sed -n 'X,Yp' file`, `head -n X file`, `tail -n X file` |
| Write a file (and create parent dirs) | `Write` | `mkdir -p ... && cat > file <<EOF` |
| Edit a file in place | `Edit` | `sed -i ...`, `awk -i inplace ...` |
| Search file contents | `Grep` (or `rg` if you genuinely need shell) | `grep -r`, `grep -rn`, `find ... -exec grep` |
| Find files by name or glob | `Glob` (or `rg --files`) | `find <path> -name '...'`, `ls -R` |
| Inspect or process N files | N parallel tool calls in one message | `for f in ...; do ... done`, `while read f; do ... done`, `xargs <cmd>` |

If you find yourself reaching for `sed`, `awk`, `for`, `while`, `xargs`, or a `grep` pipeline against the local filesystem, stop and use the native tool. The native tool path is almost always shorter to express and produces output that lands directly in the conversation rather than as truncated shell stdout.

**Specifically: never use shell `for` or `while` loops to iterate files.** Loop bodies are arbitrary code that cannot be allowlisted. To inspect ten files, issue ten parallel `Read` calls in a single message — faster, no prompts, content arrives in the conversation.

**Specifically: never use `sed -n 'X,Yp'` to read a line range.** The Bash validator rejects sed scripts other than a small set it can prove are read-only, and the `Read` tool with `offset` and `limit` does this natively.

**Specifically: for any grep pattern that contains alternation (`|` / `\|`), backticks, `${...}`, template literals, or a path with `(`, `[`, or `{` in it — use the `Grep` tool, not shell `grep`/`rg`.** The shell quoting traps around these patterns trip the validator's parser ("Parse error") and force a prompt for a command that has a native equivalent producing none.

### Construct commands that match clean allowlist patterns

The shell forms below produce permission prompts that no reasonable allowlist entry can cover. Each has a clean equivalent — prefer the clean form so the project allowlist actually applies.

**Do not append exit-code echoes.** `cmd 2>&1; echo "EXIT: $?"` and `cmd; echo "EXIT_CODE=$?"` are unnecessary — the Bash tool result already includes the exit code. Appending them turns a clean `npx eslint .` into a multi-segment command that no allowlist pattern matches, forcing a prompt.

- Yes: `npx eslint . --max-warnings=0`
- No: `npx eslint . 2>&1; echo "EXIT: $?"`

**Do not use absolute paths into `node_modules/.bin/`.** Run binaries via `npx <tool>` so the command starts with `npx`, which the allowlist can target. Absolute paths embed the project directory and can never be allowlisted generically.

- Yes: `npx tsc --noEmit -p tsconfig.app.json`
- No: `/Users/.../plano/node_modules/.bin/tsc --noEmit -p /Users/.../plano/tsconfig.app.json`

**Do not `cd <subdir> && <cmd>`.** This is a single-package repo — every npm script runs from the repo root. A `cd && ...` chain starts with `cd`, which the allowlist cannot meaningfully target.

- Yes: `npm run lint`
- No: `cd src && npx eslint .`

**Do not use `git -C <absolute-path>` when the Bash tool is already in the project's working directory.** Plain `git log`, `git diff`, `git show`, `git status`, and `git branch` are auto-allowed; the `-C <path>` prefix prevents the auto-allow from triggering and forces a prompt. Only use `-C` when you genuinely need to operate on a different repo than the cwd.

- Yes: `git log --oneline -10 -- docs/Roadmap.md`
- No: `git -C /Users/jaime/Documents/projects/obly/ log --oneline -10 -- docs/Roadmap.md`

**Do not use `find -exec`.** The `-exec` flag looks like arbitrary code execution to the permission matcher even when the executed command is read-only (`-exec ls {}`, `-exec cat {}`), so it cannot be auto-allowed and cannot be safely allowlisted with a wildcard. Use one of these instead:

- To list matches with metadata: `find <path> -name '<pat>' -type f` (default `-print` is plenty) — read the output directly.
- To grep inside matches: `rg <pattern> <path>` or `rg --files <path> | rg <name-pattern>`.
- To find files by name fast: `fd <pattern> <path>` if available.

If you genuinely need a side-effecting per-file action, make it a separate, explicit step the user can review.

**Do not use interpreter `-c` / `-e` for one-off parsing or inspection.** `python3 -c`, `node -e`, `ruby -e`, `perl -e`, `php -r`, and `lua -e` are arbitrary code execution — they cannot be safely allowlisted and they prompt every time. For the cases that drive these:

- Reading a file or a known field of a JSON/YAML file: use the `Read` tool, then inspect the content in the conversation.
- Querying a JSON file from the shell: use `jq` (auto-allowed). Example: `jq '.scripts' package.json` instead of `python3 -c "import json; ..."`.
- Querying YAML: use `yq` if available, otherwise read the file and parse it conversationally.
- Tabular text processing: `awk` and `sort -u` cover most needs and are auto-allowed.

**Do not write and execute shell scripts to `/tmp` (or any throwaway path).** `cat > /tmp/x.sh <<'EOF' ... EOF && bash /tmp/x.sh` is arbitrary code execution via heredoc, and the script content is not visible in any allowlist pattern. If a multi-step operation genuinely needs to be a script, put it under `scripts/` in the repo so it gets reviewed in a commit. For one-off operations, run the steps as discrete Bash tool calls instead.

**Do not curl Supabase REST/RPC endpoints with the service role key.** Sourcing `.env.local` and attaching `$SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` to a `curl` against `$VITE_SUPABASE_URL/rest/v1/...` is precisely the "bypass RLS / use service role keys" pattern §3 requires you to challenge. The legitimate alternatives:

- To verify a SQL function or schema object exists: query `pg_proc` / `information_schema` with the Supabase MCP `execute_sql` tool (or `list_tables` / `list_migrations`) — no service-role key in your shell, no Dashboard round-trip.
- To exercise an RPC end-to-end: write an integration test against the **local** Supabase instance with the **anon** key, not prod env vars.
- If the user explicitly asks for a one-off service-role probe, follow the ask protocol in §3 — name the user-visible risk in plain English, propose the safer alternative as the default, get a yes/no, then run the single call (not a generated allowlist pattern).

**Do not shell out to `mkdir` to prepare a directory for a new file.** The `Write` tool creates any missing parent directories automatically when it writes the first file. Calling `mkdir` separately is redundant, and `mkdir -p` against paths containing shell-glob metacharacters — parentheses, brackets, `$` — trips the harness's "no globs in write operations" guard, which cannot be allowlisted. Just use `Write` with the final file path.

**Do not use `xargs ... sh -c '...'`, `xargs ... bash -c '...'`, or any `sh -c` / `bash -c` invocation.** These are arbitrary code execution via a quoted script body and can never be allowlisted. To inspect a small set of files matched by a pattern:

- Run `find <path> -name '<pat>' -type f` (or `rg --files <path> | rg <pat>`) on its own and look at the output.
- Then call the `Read` tool once per file you actually want to inspect. This is faster than the shell pipeline, shows the content directly in the conversation, and produces no permission prompts.

For content searches, use `rg <pattern> <path>` directly — it walks files itself, so no `xargs` is needed.

**Prefer `rg` over `grep -r` for code searches.** `rg` (ripgrep) is auto-allowed, faster, respects `.gitignore` automatically (so no `node_modules` exclusion needed), and supports type filters (`-t ts -t tsx`) without `--include` flag soup. Critically: do not mix `find` syntax into `grep` — `grep -r ... ! -path "*/node_modules/*"` is not a valid composition (the `!` is `find`'s negation, not `grep`'s), it breaks the read-only-grep validator, and it forces a prompt for a command that wouldn't even work as written. The clean form:

- Yes: `rg "pinned" -t ts -t tsx src`
- No: `grep -r "pinned" src --include="*.ts" --include="*.tsx" ! -path "*/node_modules/*"`

**Do not backslash-escape paths containing parentheses or brackets (`\(...\)`, `\[...\]`) into bash arguments.** Such paths should be passed to the Read/Write/Glob/Grep tools directly, with the literal `(` and `[` characters. If a shell command genuinely needs such a path, single-quote it. The backslash-escaped form makes the harness treat the path as a glob pattern in write operations and refuses to allowlist it.

**Use `WebFetch` for documentation and web URLs, not `curl`.** A `curl` to a docs URL prompts every time because `curl` is not auto-allowable (it can POST, follow redirects to mutating endpoints, or exfiltrate data). `WebFetch` is the designed tool — it handles fetch + content extraction in one step, has its own permission model, and lets you grep the returned content in-context.

- Yes: `WebFetch(url="https://docs.aurinko.io/llms-full.txt", prompt="Find sections about ensureScopes and Mail.Send")`
- No: `curl -s -L https://docs.aurinko.io/llms-full.txt | grep -i -A 3 -B 1 "ensureScopes|nativeScopes|..."`

**Do not slice long `git diff` output with `| sed -n 'N,Mp'`.** The pipe-to-sed shape is brittle to allowlist (the matcher's greedy wildcards struggle with multi-segment commands) and prompts every time. For long diffs, redirect once and use the `Read` tool's native offset/limit instead — the Read tool exists precisely for paged reading.

- Yes: `git diff src/features/maps/api/mapsApi.ts > /tmp/maps.diff`, then `Read(path="/tmp/maps.diff", offset=300, limit=300)`.
- No: `git diff src/features/maps/api/mapsApi.ts | sed -n '300,600p'`

